{
  "answer": "The Vratiśāsana (work slug: unknown-vratisasana-d0fe75, chapter 1) is entirely dedicated to the ordinances governing the vows of the viku (ascetic/recluse). The text does not use the word 'recluse' but addresses the ascetic (viku) throughout.\n\nThe core framework is ten vows, divided into two groups of five:\n\n**Five Yamas (declared by Lord Rudra):**\n1. Ahiṁsā (non-violence) — not killing any living creature. Exceptions: ritual offerings, self-defense, killing dangerous pests. Violence initiated by the viku in a quarrel is a pantən (major transgression nullifying ascetic status).\n2. Brahmacarya (chastity) — three types: (a) śukla-brahmacārī: celibate from birth to death, never contacts a woman; (b) kṛṣṇa-brahmacārī: marries once, does not remarry after wife's death, practices dhyāna, yoga, japa, samādhi; (c) śabala/śavala-brahmacārī: may marry multiple times for procreation, but must abstain during the dry season, ninth month, and new/full moon days. Forbidden sexual relations (agamyāgamana, paradāra, gurvaṅganāgamana) are pantən.\n3. Satya (truthfulness) — true in speech, action, and vows; must follow dietary prohibitions of the Siddhānta vow (long lists of forbidden meats and drinks; e.g., palm wine is forbidden, while brəm, honey, kilang are permitted). Eating forbidden food is a pantən.\n4. Avyavahārika (non-engagement in worldly affairs) — the viku must not trade, buy, or sell. He may engage in transactions only to protect ancestral property, wife, children, or the teacher's property. He may not take interest.\n5. Asteya (non-stealing) — eight types of thieves are defined. On a journey, a viku may take small quantities of food from an abandoned garden (e.g., up to 20 cucumbers, one handful of rice) without being a thief, provided he does not carry it away in bulk.\n\n**Five Niyamas (declared by Lord Śiva):**\n1. Absence of anger (akrodha) — 'there is no enemy like anger'; anger causes the departure of the goddess Śrī.\n2. Guruśuśrūṣā (devoted service to the teacher) — constant proximity to the teacher to receive full instruction; the viku must know what to reject and adopt.\n3. Śauca (purity) — daily ritual rinsing, sun-worship, application of sacred ash (bhasma), mantra repetition; six types of bathing (āgneya, vāruṇa, brāhmya, vāyavya, mānasa, pārthiva).\n4. Āhāralāghava (lightness of diet) — contentment with simple food; no attachment to fine tastes or meat.\n5. Apramāda (vigilance) — not negligent in the teacher's instructions; practicing śivārcana, adhyāya, svādhyāya, brata, dhyāna, yoga; avoiding the houses and stalls of butchers, trappers, gamblers, potters, goldsmiths, and other outcastes.\n\nTogether, the five Yamas and five Niyamas form the daśaśīla (ten virtues). The text also provides extended lists of ten Yamas, ten Niyamas, and a tenfold dharma (dhṛti, kṣamā, dama, asteya, śauca, indriyanigraha, hrī, vidyā, satya, akrodha). Failure to protect any of these vows results in a pantən — a grave transgression that nullifies ascetic status, with no possibility of penance. The sacred implements of the viku (sacred thread, sacred ash, rosary, water vessel) become instruments of punishment in Yama's hell if the śīla is not protected.",
